Sunlight travels through Earth's atmosphere on its way to the ground. This means that when you look up at the sky, what you see is sunlight after it has passed through some of the layers in our air. Different things happen to different parts of the spectrum as they pass into and out of these atmospheric layers:
  1. **Blue light is scattered more often than other colors because there are many tiny particles (like gasses) and water vapor molecules that scatter light**. So, if there isn’t a lot of blue light reaching your eye, there likely aren’t enough of these scattering agents between your eyes and the point where all sunlight becomes visible.* Blue is generally able to reach us from farther distances. 
  2. Other wavelengths have less opportunities for their photons/waves/particles to interact with something else or be absorbed before getting to earth, so those specific wave lengths will show less frequently even though we can still sense them but just not seeing it directly* The rest of the visible light frequencies (green-orange-red etc..) have fewer chances to be scattered around by oxygen and nitrogen atoms within the troposphere before hitting our pupils*. * These statements may only apply to an empty 'clean' environment without any clouds present... In presence of clouds this information could be quite opposite! 
